<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-04-08T04:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-04-08T04:00:00-05:00" n="313" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d313">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">125.494/5: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-04-08T17:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">April 8,
                                        1927—5 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received April 8—4:27
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>385. My 260, March 26, 4 p.m.<note n="19" xml:id="d313fn19">Not
                                printed.</note> Americans in Kalgan have been instructed to
                            withdraw. I respectfully repeat recommendation that consulate there be
                            closed, as soon as Americans evacuated.<note n="20" xml:id="d313fn20">The consulate at Kalgan was temporarily closed April 23. It was
                                permanently closed September 30 and the consular district
                                incorporated into the Tientsin consular district.</note></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>